ce:section.ce:para:
The straightforward strategy for M/COFs synthesis is encapsulation pre-synthesized metal nanoscale particles during the preparation of COFs or mixing with prepared COFs by physical adsorption and chemical adsorption (Table 1
                        ) (Chen et al., 2022; Cheng et al., 2022; He et al., 2022). The physical adsorption mainly through electrostatic interaction usually cause lower loading efficiency of metal nanoscale particles, while the chemical adsorption through coordination or covalent interaction between metal nanoscale particles and COFs skeleton could improve the loading efficiency (Li et al., 2024d). In 2024, Zhu et al. developed a universal mechanochemical synthesis method for embedding pre-synthesized diverse oil- and water-soluble AuNCs within various reticular frameworks via solid-state mechanochemical encapsulation process with high metal loading efficiency (Fig. 1
                        ). The obtained Au25@COF-TpPa displayed uniformly dispersed AuNCs in COF-TpPa without aggregation (Li et al., 2024d). However, the adsorption method could not mitigate the size of metal nanoscale particles in M/COFs.

The in-situ reduction to prepare M@COFs means embedding metal nanoscale particles into the pores of COFs upon the existence of metal precursor and reducing atmosphere, which could be categorized through different metal reduction pathways: deposition, impregnation-pyrolysis and “one-step” reduction. The deposition method is developed to load metal nanoscale nanoparticles mainly utilizing light, vapor deposition or electrodeposition without addition of external reducing agents, which preserves the original crystal porous structure of COFs and reduces the potential damage to the crystal structure (Table 2
                        ) (Xu et al., 2021). For example, Deng et al. synthesized PY-DHBD-COF and in-situ photo-deposited platinum nanoclusters (PtNCs), which were uniformly dispersed on the surface layer of COF. Notably, as shown in Fig. 2
                        , with the further increasing in Pt loading, the size of PtNCs gradually grows (Li et al., 2022a). Shao et al. reported a method to regulate the dispersion of Cu in the COF network from single atoms (SAs) to NCs by adjusting the electrodeposition duration. The electrodeposited CuNCs were uniformly distributed in the COF network with a diameter of 1–2 nm (Chandran et al., 2022).

The impregnation-pyrolysis method to synthesize M@COFs mainly includes two steps. The first step is pre-introducing metal ions into COFs skeletons by impregnating COFs into solution of metal precursors. Then reducing metal precursors to nanoscale particles by pyrolyzing the powder of COFs loaded with metal ions (Table 3
                        ) (Li et al., 2021). For example, Jiang group loaded Pt2+ into pores of TP-BPY-COF by coordination with bipyridine units from the BPY units to obtain Pt-COF. Then the Pt-COF was carbonized at 800 °C to yield Pt-COF800, which showed highly dispersed Pt nanoparticles with narrow size distribution on the TP-BPY-COF-derived carbon (Fig. 3
                        A and B). As shown in SEM and TEM images, the introduction of Pt nanoparticles could well maintained the layered structure of COFs supports (Li et al., 2023d). However, the pyrolysis reduction usually needs high temperature and gas atmosphere, which may bring sophisticate procedure and large energy consumption.

The general paradigm for metal loading into COFs using“one-step” reduction involves soaking routine COFs in solution containing metal precursors upon reducing environment including stirring or heating directly or adding external reducing agents (such as NaBH4, Sodium citrate) (Ding et al., 2011; Pachfule et al., 2014b). This method has become the most widely used approach for the preparation of M@COFs due to its universality and simplicity. However, the addition of reducing agents and other reagents may introduce impurities, and the size and distribution of nanoscale particles cannot be precisely controlled in the COF pores potentially leading to pore blockage (Xu et al., 2021). For instance, Banerjee et al. prepared Au-loaded COFs by reduction of pristine COFs and HAuCl4 mixtures (Pachfule et al., 2014a). However, the particle size (5 ± 3 nm) of AuNPs was widely distributed although at a low loading amount of Au (∼1.2 wt %), and significantly larger than the pore size of COFs (∼1.8 nm). Afterwards, Liu et al. designed a series of polyimide-based triazine-cored COFs (PIT-COFs) with different aromatic diimides to support metal (Fe, Ni, Ru and Rh) nanoparticles by grinding metal precursors with NaBH4 powder (as shown in Fig. 4
                        A) (Li et al., 2024b). The TEM images exhibited small-sized MNPs (1–3 nm) with spherical morphology of Fe@COFMA-PT, Ru@COFMA-PT and Rh@COFMA-PT, while metal nanosheets were observed at Ni@COFMA-PT (Fig. 4B). So far, more and more metals such as Au, Ag, Pd, Pt, Ru, Co, Fe, Bi, Sn and Ir NCs or NPs have been embedded into COFs supports successfully (Table 4
                        ). Moreover, the size of metal particles can be tailored by tuning the reducing conditions.

Recently, pore wall molecular engineering strategy of in-situ reduction method have drawn special attention, which aims to load ultrafine and highly dispersed metal nanoclusters into COF supports via modifying COFs skeletons with strong metal anchoring groups like thioether and phosphine groups as nucleation sites (Table 5
                        ) (Guo et al. 2024; Lu et al., 2017). This method could solve the randomness and looseness, enabling more precise control over the size and loading position of nanoscale particles on the COFs supports to a certain extent. For example, Zhang et al. reported the first example of a PPh3-based crystalline COF (Phos-COF-1), where the PPh3 moieties served as coordination sites for metal ions. Ultrafine (<2 nm) monometallic as well as bimetallic nanoparticles, PdNPs, PtNPs, AuNPs, and PdAuNPs, with narrow size distribution have been successfully embedded in COFs pores (Tao et al., 2020). Lu et al. synthesized a 2D COF postmodified with thiol chains (COF-S-SH), where the thiol groups served as nucleation sites for metal precursors (Fig. 5
                        A) (Deng et al., 2020). Upon the addition of HAuCl4 and L-glutathione (L-GSH) at 80 °C, highly dispersed and ultrafine AuNCs with an average diameter of 1.8 ± 0.2 nm were anchored inside the pores of the COF support (Fig. 5B). In 2024, Liao et al. synthesized a carboxy-functionalized COF-COOH via the Doebner-Miller reaction, where the carboxyl group served as growth sites for the AuNCs. The TEM images of obtained Au@COF showed that the AuNCs were uniformly distributed on the COF-COOH skeleton with an average diameter of 1.35 nm (Shang et al., 2023).
